+    Like the :func:`~jinja-filters.sort` filter, sorting and grouping is
+    case-insensitive by default. The ``key`` for each group will have
+    the case of the first item in that group of values. For example, if
+    a list of users has cities ``["CA", "NY", "ca"]``, the "CA" and "ca"
+    entries will be grouped together.
+
+    You can control case sensitivity with the ``case_sensitive`` parameter.
+
+    .. sourcecode:: jinja
+
+        <ul>{% for city, items in users|groupby("city", case_sensitive=true) %}
+          <li>{{ city }}: {{ items|map(attribute="name")|join(", ") }}</li>
+        {% endfor %}</ul>
+
+    You can also specify ``with_counts=True`` to include the number of
+    items in each group, yielding ``(grouper, list, count)`` tuples
+    instead. This avoids needing ``{{ items|list|length }}`` to get the
+    size of a group.
+
+    .. sourcecode:: jinja
+
+        <ul>{% for city, items, count in users|groupby("city", with_counts=True) %}
+          <li>{{ city }} ({{ count }})</li>
+        {% endfor %}</ul>
+
+    .. versionchanged:: 3.1
+        Added the ``case_sensitive`` and ``with_counts`` parameters.
+
     .. versionchanged:: 3.0
         Added the ``default`` parameter.
 
     .. versionchanged:: 2.6
         The attribute supports dot notation for nested access.
     """
